
5d-Block Double-Zeta Basis Set Archive
======================================


Date: 04 Jun 2010


When publishing work that uses these basis sets, please use the following citation:

K.G. Dyall, Theor. Chem. Acc. (2004) 112, 403; K. G. Dyall and A. S. P. Gomes, 
Theor. Chem. Acc. (2010) 125:97. Available from the Dirac web site, http://dirac.chem.sdu.dk.



This archive contains the exponents and the SCF spinor or orbital coefficients, 
given with respect to normalized (spherical or 2-spinor) Gaussian functions, for
the double-zeta basis sets described in the above articles.  

The primitive basis set is a 24s 19p 12d 8f set, including functions for the 6p.
This set supersedes the earlier 22s 19p 12d 8f set. In the current set the s set
has been augmented and reoptimized, the d set has been reoptimized on the
configuration average of the d^n s^2 and d^n+1 s^1 configurations, and the p and
f sets also reoptimized. 

NOTE: Functions are counted from the function with the smallest exponent to the largest. 

The SCF exponent sets were generated as follows:

* Optimization of the s, p, d, and f sets separately, on the total energy of the
  configuration average of the d^n s^2 and d^n+1 s^1 configurations
* Addition of 2 exponents for the 6p, optimized with reoptimization of the
  exponents for the 3p-5p outer antinodes on the total energy of the d^n s^2
  configuration
* Addition of the correlating f exponent to the f set with reoptimization of the
  other 7 f exponents.

In all the following descriptions, this is the set referred to as the SCF 
exponent set. 

The correlating exponents were generated as follows

* An f exponent for the 5d and 6s was optimized in MR-SDCI calculations on the
  ground configuration.
* A g exponent for the 4f and was optimized in MR-DCI calculations on the
  ground configuration, with double excitations from the 4f shell into the g
  shell coupled to J=0.

The exponents for 5d dipole polarization were generated as follows:

* A polarizing f exponent was optimized on the polarizability of the 5d shell
  with 5d -> f excitations in the perturbing space. 

The contractions are taken from SCF calculations on the weighted average of
the d^n s^2, d^n+1 s^1, and d^n p^2 configurations with weight ratio
45%:45%:10%, except for Hg, where the d^n s^2 and d^n p^2 configurations are
used with weight ratio 90%:10%.



The archive is set out as follows.

1. Exponents and SCF coefficients for Dirac-Hartree-Fock wave functions, in order
   of Z. The large component functions are given first, followed by the small 
   component functions. Both components are labelled with the large component
   symmetry type, but the primitive functions for the small component are
   those obtained by restricted kinetic balance from the large component.
   The spin-orbit components have a "-" label for j=l-1/2 and a "+" label for
   j=l+1/2.

2. Exponents and SCF coefficients for spin-free modified Dirac-Hartree-Fock wave
   functions, in order of Z. The large component functions are given first, 
   followed by the pseudo-large component functions, then the Foldy-Wouthuysen
   transformed large component functions. Note that all components have the same
   symmetry type. 

3. Exponents of valence correlating and dipole polarizing functions.

4. Exponents of core correlating functions.


Basis set construction.
----------------------

Contracted basis sets can be constructed by adding primitive functions to the SCF 
set. These basis sets are described below. Note that the term "double zeta" applies 
to the s and p set, and the d set is triple zeta. This is a result of keeping a 
reasonable energy balance for the basis sets. 

NOTE: Functions are counted in increasing exponent size, from the smallest to the largest.

The valence space is defined here as the 5d, 6s, and 6p orbitals. 

1. Valence flexibility. To the SCF functions, add the following:

   2nd s primitive from the SCF set 
   2nd p primitive from the SCF set
   1st and 2nd d primitives from the SCF set
   1st f primitive from the SCF set (correlating f function)

2. Valence + outer core. This set adds the outer-core correlation from the 5s and 5p
   shells. To set 1, add the following functions: 

   4th s primitive from the SCF set 
   3rd p primitive from the SCF set
   3rd d primitive from the SCF set

   If linear dependence is encountered in the d set, do not uncontract the 2nd primitive.

3. Valence + outer core + 4f. This set adds correlation from the 4f shell.  To set 2,
   add the following functions: 

   4th d primitive from the SCF set
   2nd f primitive from the SCF set
   Correlating g function for 4f correlation

   This choice reflects only 4f correlation with a change in angular momentum of
   1 unit. If it is necessary to uncontract an s and p primitive, add the 5th s and
   p primitives to the set. 

4. Dipole polarization of the 5d. To any of the above basis sets, add the polarizing
   f function.
